-- Lesson 1: Automated Rules & Scheduling
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Automated Rules & Scheduling</h2><h3>Streamlining Campaign Management with Automation</h3><p>Automated rules and scheduling reduce manual work and enable 24/7 campaign optimization. These powerful features handle routine tasks automatically based on predefined conditions. Mastering automation improves efficiency and performance while freeing time for strategy.</p><h3>What are Automated Rules?</h3><p>Conditional actions triggered by performance metrics. If-then logic for campaign management. Pause underperformers automatically. Increase budgets on winners. Send notifications for important changes. Runs continuously without manual intervention. Scales management capabilities significantly.</p><h3>Types of Automated Rules</h3><p>Budget rules: adjust spending based on performance. Status rules: pause or activate campaigns. Notification rules: alert on important events. Bid rules: modify bidding strategies. Multiple rule types available. Combine for comprehensive automation. Choose based on management needs.</p><h3>Creating Automated Rules</h3><p>Select campaigns, ad sets, or ads. Define conditions triggering action. Set performance thresholds. Choose action to take. Specify time range for evaluation. Set rule schedule. Test before full deployment. Monitor rule performance regularly.</p><h3>Budget Automation Rules</h3><p>Increase budget when ROAS exceeds target. Decrease spend if CPA too high. Pause if daily spend limit reached. Scale winners automatically. Protect against overspend. Optimize allocation continuously. Budget rules maximize efficiency.</p><h3>Performance-Based Pause Rules</h3><p>Pause if CPA exceeds threshold. Stop if ROAS falls below minimum. Pause high-frequency ads. Deactivate low-CTR campaigns. Prevent wasted spend automatically. Include sufficient data requirements. Avoid premature pausing.</p><h3>Notification Rules</h3><p>Alert when campaigns pause. Notify on budget depletion. Warning for performance changes. Daily summary emails. Custom alerts for key events. Stay informed without constant monitoring. Proactive management through notifications.</p><h3>Scheduling Campaigns</h3><p>Set start and end dates. Schedule by day of week. Time-of-day targeting. Seasonal campaign automation. Event-based scheduling. Automatic activation and deactivation. Perfect timing without manual intervention.</p><h3>Dayparting Strategies</h3><p>Show ads during peak performance hours. Pause during low-conversion periods. Adjust bids by time of day. Maximize efficiency through timing. Analyze hourly performance first. Schedule based on data. Timing optimization improves results.</p><h3>Rule Best Practices</h3><p>Start with simple rules. Test thoroughly before scaling. Include sufficient data requirements. Avoid conflicting rules. Monitor rule actions regularly. Document rule logic. Review and update periodically. Systematic approach prevents issues.</p><h3>Common Rule Mistakes</h3><p>Too aggressive thresholds. Insufficient data requirements. Conflicting rule logic. Not monitoring rule actions. Over-automation reducing control. Ignoring learning phases. Not testing before deployment. Avoid these pitfalls.</p><h3>Advanced Automation Strategies</h3><p>Layered rules for complex logic. Coordinated campaign management. Cross-campaign optimization. Sequential rule execution. Sophisticated automation for scale. Requires careful planning. Advanced users benefit most.</p><h3>Third-Party Automation Tools</h3><p>Revealbot for advanced rules. Madgicx for AI optimization. AdEspresso for simplified management. Hootsuite Ads for multi-platform. More features than native tools. Additional cost consideration. Evaluate based on needs.</p><h3>Monitoring Automated Actions</h3><p>Review rule activity regularly. Check for unexpected behaviors. Verify rules working as intended. Adjust thresholds based on results. Override when necessary. Automation assists, not replaces judgment. Active oversight essential.</p><h3>Balancing Automation and Control</h3><p>Automate routine tasks. Maintain human oversight for strategy. Use rules for efficiency. Keep creative control. Automation handles execution. Humans provide direction. Optimal balance varies by business.</p><h3>Scaling with Automation</h3><p>Manage more campaigns efficiently. Consistent optimization 24/7. Faster response to changes. Reduced management overhead. Enables growth without proportional team growth. Automation critical for scale.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Automated rules handle routine optimization tasks automatically</li><li>Budget, pause, and notification rules most common types</li><li>Set clear conditions and include sufficient data requirements</li><li>Scheduling enables perfect timing without manual intervention</li><li>Dayparting optimizes by time of day based on performance</li><li>Start simple, test thoroughly, monitor regularly</li><li>Third-party tools offer advanced automation features</li><li>Balance automation efficiency with human strategic oversight</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Advanced Bidding: Cost Caps & Bid Caps.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Automated Rules & Scheduling' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);

-- Lesson 2: Advanced Bidding: Cost Caps & Bid Caps
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Advanced Bidding: Cost Caps & Bid Caps</h2><h3>Controlling Costs While Maximizing Volume</h3><p>Advanced bidding strategies provide more control over campaign costs and delivery. Cost caps and bid caps enable advertisers to balance efficiency with scale. Understanding these tools helps optimize campaigns for specific business requirements and constraints.</p><h3>Bidding Strategy Overview</h3><p>Lowest cost: maximize results within budget. Cost cap: control cost per result. Bid cap: set maximum bid amount. Each strategy serves different objectives. Choose based on business goals. Understanding options enables better decisions.</p><h3>Lowest Cost Bidding</h3><p>Default and simplest strategy. Facebook optimizes for maximum results. No cost controls applied. Best performance in many cases. May have cost fluctuations. Works well with sufficient budget. Recommended starting point for most.</p><h3>What is Cost Cap?</h3><p>Set maximum acceptable cost per result. Facebook delivers results at or below cap. Balances cost control with volume. More results than bid cap typically. Flexible optimization within constraint. Good for predictable economics. Popular for performance campaigns.</p><h3>When to Use Cost Cap</h3><p>Need predictable cost per acquisition. Have clear profitability threshold. Want to scale while controlling costs. Balancing efficiency and volume. Established campaigns with data. Know acceptable CPA or ROAS. Most common advanced strategy.</p><h3>Setting Cost Cap Amounts</h3><p>Base on business economics. Calculate maximum profitable CPA. Consider profit margins. Account for lifetime value. Start slightly above current performance. Adjust based on delivery. Too low limits delivery. Too high wastes budget.</p><h3>What is Bid Cap?</h3><p>Set maximum bid in auctions. Strict control over bid amounts. May limit delivery significantly. More predictable costs. Lower volume than cost cap. Advanced strategy requiring expertise. Use when absolute cost control critical.</p><h3>When to Use Bid Cap</h3><p>Absolute cost control required. Limited budget with strict constraints. Highly competitive auctions. Testing price sensitivity. Advanced optimization scenarios. Understand trade-offs first. Not recommended for beginners.</p><h3>Cost Cap vs Bid Cap</h3><p>Cost cap more flexible, better delivery. Bid cap stricter control, may limit volume. Cost cap easier to manage. Bid cap requires more expertise. Cost cap recommended for most. Bid cap for specific scenarios. Choose based on priorities.</p><h3>Minimum ROAS Bidding</h3><p>Set minimum return on ad spend target. Facebook optimizes to meet ROAS goal. Good for e-commerce campaigns. Requires conversion value tracking. Balances revenue and spend. Alternative to cost cap. Useful for profit-focused campaigns.</p><h3>Optimizing with Cost Caps</h3><p>Start conservative, adjust gradually. Monitor delivery and performance. Increase cap if delivery limited. Decrease if costs too high. Test different cap levels. Find optimal balance. Continuous optimization improves results.</p><h3>Common Cost Cap Mistakes</h3><p>Setting cap too low. Changing too frequently. Not allowing learning phase. Unrealistic expectations. Ignoring delivery issues. Not testing different levels. Comparing to incompatible benchmarks. Avoid these errors.</p><h3>Advanced Bidding Strategies</h3><p>Dynamic cost caps by audience. Seasonal cap adjustments. Layered bidding approaches. Coordinated multi-campaign bidding. Sophisticated optimization for experts. Requires significant experience. Build on fundamentals first.</p><h3>Monitoring Bidding Performance</h3><p>Track delivery and pacing. Monitor cost per result trends. Compare to targets. Analyze auction competition. Assess volume vs efficiency trade-off. Regular review enables optimization. Data-driven bidding decisions.</p><h3>When to Switch Strategies</h3><p>Performance not meeting goals. Delivery issues persistent. Business requirements changed. Testing different approaches. Market conditions shifted. Strategic flexibility important. Document changes and results.</p><h3>Best Practices</h3><p>Start with lowest cost to establish baseline. Introduce caps based on data. Set realistic targets. Allow sufficient learning time. Monitor delivery closely. Adjust systematically. Test different strategies. Choose based on business needs.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Advanced bidding provides more cost control than lowest cost</li><li>Cost cap sets maximum acceptable cost per result</li><li>Bid cap sets maximum bid amount in auctions</li><li>Cost cap balances control and volume better than bid cap</li><li>Minimum ROAS bidding optimizes for return targets</li><li>Set caps based on business economics and data</li><li>Monitor delivery and adjust caps systematically</li><li>Start simple, advance to complex strategies with experience</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Retargeting with Catalogs & Dynamic Ads.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Advanced Bidding: Cost Caps & Bid Caps' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);
